## What autocorrelation on the wave signal tells us (use case 1)

The signal within the stable wave window is `~N` periods of (nearly) sinusoidal motion. The autocorrelation at lag `T = 1/f` should be close to 1.0 if the wave is perfectly regular. The **decay envelope** of the autocorrelation peaks (at lags T, 2T, 3T…) tells you how much period-to-period amplitude/phase jitter there is.

Key scalar you can extract: **autocorrelation at lag = 1 period**. Call it `"wave_stability"`. A value near 1.0 = clean repeating wave; lower = more variation run-to-run or period-to-period. This is a natural quality flag for the OUT/IN amplitude estimate.

A second useful thing: **per-period amplitude sequence** — take the signal between each consecutive pair of upcrossings, compute (P97.5−P2.5)/2 for each period, and look at the std/mean ratio. If the wave is ramping up or decaying across periods, the OUT/IN estimate is unreliable.

